
McDonald's Corporation (NYSE: MCD) has more than 38,000 restaurant locations globally in 119 countries, with 93% owned and operated by franchisees.﻿﻿ The company announced its Q2 2020 results on July 28, 2020, reporting $3.76 billion in revenue, a 30% decrease from the $5.41 billion reported in Q2 2019.﻿﻿
 
Here are the four largest mutual fund holders of McDonald's.
 
The largest mutual fund holder, Vanguard Total Stock Market Index Fund (VTSMX), owns 21.2 million shares of McDonald's, or 2.85% of the company, as of June 30, 2020.﻿﻿ ﻿﻿ This mutual fund is designed to give broad exposure to the total U.S. stock market by including small-cap, mid-cap and large-cap growth and value stocks. The fund has $872.2 billion in net assets invested across 3,530 stocks, with MCD making up 0.43% of the company's total portfolio.﻿﻿ The fund is closed to new investors, but Vanguard Total Stock Market Index Fund Admiral Shares (VTSAX) area available with a minimum investment of $3,000.﻿﻿ 
 
The Vanguard 500 Index Fund (VFINX) owns 15.4 million shares of McDonald's. The fund is invested in 510 stocks covering a diversified spectrum of the largest U.S. companies, mirroring the S&P 500 Index. The total net assets are $533.6 billion, with 0.53% of the fund's total portfolio invested in MCD. VFINX's 15.4 million MCD shares represent 2.07% of the company.﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿
 
The SPDR S&P 500 ETF (SPY) is famed for being the first ever Exchange Traded Fund and tracks the S&P 500 just like VFINX. SPDR's net assets amount to $301.4 billion, with 0.59% of its portfolio invested in McDonald's stock.﻿﻿ As of October 2020, SPY owns 7.8 million shares of McDonald's, or 1.05% of the company.﻿﻿
 
The fourth-largest mutual fund holder of McDonald's is the American Funds Income Fund of America (AMECX). This mutual fund is invested in more than 690 stocks, with investments in both the stock and bond markets. AMECX owns 7.6 million shares of MCD, or about 0.98% of the company, as of October 2018. McDonald's stock makes up 1.23% of the fund's net assets, and the total assets in its portfolio amount to $105.6 billion.
 
This $235.2 billion-institutional fund tracks the S&P 500 Index following a passively-managed, full-replication approach invested in 506 stocks. The Vanguard Institutional Index Fund Institutional Shares (VINIX) owned 7.4 million shares of MCD as of October 2018, approximately 0.95% of the company. McDonald's represents 0.53% of this mutual fund's total portfolio assets. This is the institutional version of the Vanguard 500 Index Fund and is available only to institutional investors. The minimum investment is $5 million.
